years ago,about black people sending their kids back to Barbados,Jamaica etc to get a proper education.Is that still a trend? &#10;State systems are designed to turn out losers.There are not enough good jobs,nice houses,charming prospective spouses to go round. The teachers must get the message,fairly soon in their careers.They just have to make sure that the statistics look right for the inspectors. &#10;Out in the 'sticks'(where I had to move from the city,to find employment),it is noticeable that the well off kids,nearly all 'go to uni',as if it is a birthright. The children of the working class parents can tend to strugggle in the education and jobs market. Perhaps it is an ecomomic as well as a racial issue. &#10;Boys have always been 'challenging'.A family whose sons I grew up with,sent 2 out 3 of the boys in the forces,to 'straighten them out'.It worked. Another problem is that we are living in a 'post industrial society'. There are no longer many factory jobs for the less educationally rewarded. &#10;A thought occurs.How do your boys do with socialisation? Does their unconvential teaching arrangements effect their friendships with other kids? Do you let them out to play football? &#10;As Paul Simon sang,years ago,&quot;When I think of all the crap I learned in HIgh School&quot;."/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1576" language="en" documentId="744" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="itin78" date="07 January 2011 11:18am" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/9049843" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="18" thumbsDown="0" origId="744" notes="" title="Why I home school my children"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="12"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="13" end="270"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="271" end="425"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="426" end="699"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="55" sofa="1" begin="700" end="1014"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="59" sofa="1" begin="1015" end="1306"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="63" sofa="1" begin="1307" end="1490"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="67" sofa="1" begin="1491" end="1576"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51 55 59 63 67"/></xmi:XMI>